    "lesson_content_markdown":  "# Plans vs. Predictions\n\nIn English, we talk about the future in different ways depending on our situation.\n\n### 1. Future Plans: Be + Going to\n\nWe use **going to** when we have already decided on a plan.\n\n- **Formula**: Be Verb (am/is/are) + **going to** + do something.\n- **Example**: I **am going to study** in the library tonight. (I already decided this!)\n- **Example**: They **are going to go** to the cafeteria after class.\n\n### 2. General Predictions: Will\n\nWe use **will** when we talk about a general idea or guess about the future.\n\n- **Formula**: **will** + do something.\n- **Example**: I think it **will rain** tomorrow. (This is my guess.)\n- **Example**: The library **will be** busy on Monday.\n\n### 3. Decisions Right Now: Will\n\nUse **will** when you decide something exactly at this moment.\n\n- **Example**: Wait! I **will help** you with those bags.\n- **Example**: I\u0027m cold. I **will close** the window now.\n\n---",
